WEBVTT

00:00.290 --> 00:08.698
As we move from gathering to listening, our scripture reading today is from the Book of Luke chapter 18 verses 9 to 14.

00:10.200 --> 00:17.327
To some who are confident of their own righteousness and look down on everyone else, Jesus told this parable.

00:18.548 --> 00:24.354
Two men went up to the temple to pray, one a Pharisee and the other a tax collector.

00:25.435 --> 00:28.018
The Pharisee stood by himself and prayed,

00:28.738 --> 00:37.246
God, I thank you that I'm not like other people, robbers, evildoers, adulterers, or even like this tax collector.

00:38.107 --> 00:41.190
I fast twice a week and give a tenth of all I get.

00:42.931 --> 00:45.934
But the tax collector stood at a distance.

00:45.954 --> 00:52.020
He would not even look up to heaven, but beat his breast and said, God, have mercy on me, a sinner.

00:53.781 --> 00:58.706
I tell you that this man, rather than the other, went home justified before God.

00:59.234 --> 01:05.465
For all those who exalt themselves will be humbled, and those who humble themselves will be exalted.

01:06.307 --> 01:07.609
This is the word of the Lord.

01:08.270 --> 01:09.232
Thanks be to God.

01:14.080 --> 01:14.902
Thank you, Masha.

01:15.102 --> 01:15.703
More church.

01:16.685 --> 01:17.967
Good to see you all today.

01:18.007 --> 01:19.810
My name's Pete, and one of the pastors here.

01:19.971 --> 01:21.874
And it is so good to be with you.

01:22.082 --> 01:26.570
I was on the Southern Civil Rights pilgrimage these last nine days.

01:26.630 --> 01:31.660
We got home late last night and missed you guys, but happy to be back.

01:32.742 --> 01:36.869
I want to take just a moment and try to give you a snapshot of our trip.

01:36.949 --> 01:43.922
It won't really do justice to the journey that we were on, but I wanted to at least give you a quick overview.

01:44.130 --> 02:01.842
We started in New Orleans and then worked our way up to Jackson, Mississippi through the Mississippi Delta up into Memphis, Tennessee and then down into Alabama where we went to Montgomery and then Selma and finished in Birmingham.

02:01.922 --> 02:14.770
And really, the movement of the trip was designed to follow the narrative of the black struggle for liberation and reconciliation from slavery

02:14.882 --> 02:18.467
through segregation into the modern day.

02:18.487 --> 02:30.444
And so we were guided by a fellow named John Williams from the Center for Racial Reconciliation out of Pasadena, and John was an incredible host and guide for us.

02:31.105 --> 02:38.395
And let me just give you a couple quick snapshots from our trip that give you an idea of the kinds of things we are doing.

02:38.476 --> 02:40.178
So starting in New Orleans,

02:40.770 --> 02:44.934
and we had an opportunity to learn the history of the slave trade there.

02:45.694 --> 03:02.609
We did a walking tour with a guy who's been there on the ground for many decades now, learning about the largest slave port in the United States and the ways in which that city is still haunted by the ghosts of slavery today.

03:03.430 --> 03:10.756
Then we had a chance to go up to Memphis and visit the Civil Rights Museum, which is housed at the Lorraine Motel, the exact spot

03:10.736 --> 03:13.481
where Dr. King was assassinated.

03:14.022 --> 03:18.390
And so that spot there with the wreath is where he was killed.

03:19.051 --> 03:25.123
And the Civil Rights Museum that's there is incredibly powerful and moving.

03:25.884 --> 03:31.154
We went from there to Jackson, Mississippi, where we got to hear stories from

03:31.618 --> 03:45.010
Several civil rights legends, the folks that are sitting down in the front row, that are all in their 80s or 90s now, who were gracious enough to spend a day with us telling us their stories.

03:45.090 --> 03:54.753
of marching, of sitting in, of writing the bus when they weren't supposed to and not writing the bus when they were supposed to.

03:55.214 --> 04:03.474
The one guy on the far right sitting down Hezekiah was arrested and sent to jail 109 times.

04:03.618 --> 04:09.567
simply for using the bathroom he wasn't supposed to or sitting at the counter he wasn't supposed to.

04:10.007 --> 04:15.055
So these legends shared their lives and their stories with us and it was unbelievable.

04:16.036 --> 04:25.490
We went to the Peace and Justice Memorial in Montgomery, Alabama, which really focuses in on the story of lynching.

04:25.602 --> 04:27.225
in the United States.

04:27.305 --> 04:36.460
And I would say personally, along with the Holocaust Museum in Jerusalem, this is the most powerful museum experience I've ever had.

04:37.282 --> 04:44.434
Each one of those memorials that you see hanging from the ceiling above represents a county in the U.S. where

04:44.514 --> 04:47.058
Black Americans were lynched.

04:48.240 --> 04:50.384
Incredibly moving experience.

04:50.805 --> 04:55.312
In Birmingham, we had an opportunity to meet with the fifth little girl, as she's called.

04:56.454 --> 05:08.114
Sarah Rudolph Collins, and this was at the site of the 16th Street Baptist Church bombing, where four Black little girls were killed one Sunday morning.

05:08.226 --> 05:21.215
Sarah was there in the restroom with them and she lost an eye from the shrapnel but lived to tell about it and now in her 80s has devoted the rest of her days to telling this story.

05:21.415 --> 05:22.738
We got to meet with her.

05:23.202 --> 05:41.970
And then finally, we got to walk across the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma, Alabama, where this march from Selma to Montgomery began and to follow the lead of our black elders who have so resiliently resisted.

05:42.498 --> 05:49.417
the injustice and oppression that they have experienced for many centuries in our country now.

05:49.918 --> 05:57.138
And so it is so hard to summarize and encapsulate everything that we went through, but I come home

05:57.186 --> 06:07.375
I'm incredibly grateful for the opportunity to go, grateful for your prayers, and grateful for our team from Antioch here that went along as a learning community.

06:07.455 --> 06:08.936
So this is our group.

06:09.156 --> 06:11.799
There were 20 of us with our guides.

06:11.979 --> 06:19.225
You can see we've got some middle schoolers all the way up to some grandpas and grandmas and everything in between.

06:19.285 --> 06:22.128
And we had an amazing time together.

06:22.188 --> 06:24.189
So who's here from the trip?

06:24.310 --> 06:27.172
Who made a, hey, look at you guys.

06:27.152 --> 06:30.977
in the first service, yeah.

06:30.997 --> 06:33.280
We got home at 1 a.m. this morning, so.

06:34.121 --> 06:45.055
And in addition to it being powerful and provocative, it was also just a really unifying and enjoyable time together.

06:45.075 --> 06:49.520
They do food real good in the South, if you didn't know that.

06:49.621 --> 06:51.763
So we ate a lot, and we ate well.

06:51.883 --> 06:52.624
I kid you not.

06:52.644 --> 06:53.626
I weighed in this morning.

06:54.367 --> 06:57.010
I gained nine pounds this week.

06:57.570 --> 07:00.675
So that's, I didn't know you could do that.

07:00.695 --> 07:04.421
Like, that's the opposite of giving birth, I think.

07:04.842 --> 07:09.249
And so I'm bringing home memories and other things.

07:09.609 --> 07:20.186
But I'm grateful for the chance any of those folks who raised their hands would love to chat with you, to share some of their stories and impressions and that sort of thing.

07:20.266 --> 07:22.770
It really was a wonderful time.

07:22.946 --> 07:29.618
We're gonna dive in to week six of our fall vision series that's entitled the whole gospel.

07:29.762 --> 07:32.265
both and faith and in either or world.

07:32.826 --> 07:45.402
And really, this is a series that's designed to help us understand the unique distinctions that God has given us as a church and what it is that makes Antioch Antioch.

07:45.462 --> 07:53.812
And so we're using this chart, which is one of the ways that I've found helpful to explain sort of what our church is all about.

07:54.353 --> 07:55.314
For the past,

07:55.458 --> 08:07.634
couple hundred years in the United States, you've really had these two primary streams within Protestant Christianity, which we might call mainline Protestantism and evangelicalism.

08:07.778 --> 08:10.000
Neither of those terms mean anything to you.

08:10.041 --> 08:10.721
That's okay.

08:10.741 --> 08:11.843
You don't need to know them.

08:12.523 --> 08:25.838
But what I've found is that if you pay attention that you'll find that most churches fit pretty nicely under one of these headings in terms of the aspects of Christian faith and practice they tend to emphasize.

08:26.559 --> 08:32.746
And in this series, what we're doing is asking the question, what if we didn't have to choose a side?

08:33.447 --> 08:36.370
What if we took rather than an either or approach

08:36.642 --> 08:39.627
What if we took a both and approach to the Christian faith?

08:40.207 --> 08:43.412
What if we didn't have to settle for just one half of the gospel?

08:43.953 --> 08:47.679
What would it look like to be a church that's chasing after the whole gospel?

08:48.020 --> 08:50.583
And so that's what we're doing in this series.

08:50.664 --> 08:53.728
We've covered several sin, several subjects so far.

08:54.269 --> 08:57.434
This morning, we come to the subject of sin.

08:57.454 --> 08:57.534
Yay.

08:59.537 --> 09:05.266
So the easiest way to understand sin

09:05.410 --> 09:12.400
is to look at what God's world was like before sin and what it will be like after sin.

09:13.021 --> 09:23.937
So in the Bible, the first two chapters, Genesis 1 and 2, and the last two chapters, Revelation 21 and 22, give us a picture of a world without sin.

09:23.997 --> 09:30.086
And the word that the Bible uses to describe a world without sin is shalom.

09:30.887 --> 09:33.010
It's the Hebrew word for peace.

09:33.474 --> 09:45.491
And the Christian philosopher Cornelius Plantinga sums it up really nicely, and I'll just read how he describes what Shalom is all about.

09:46.012 --> 09:55.826
He says, the webbing together of God, humans, and all creation in justice, fulfillment, and delight is what the Hebrew prophets call Shalom.

09:56.194 --> 10:02.584
We call it peace, but it means far more than mere peace of mind or a ceasefire between enemies.

10:03.185 --> 10:08.294
In the Bible, Shalom means universal flourishing, wholeness and delight.

10:09.195 --> 10:13.002
A rich state of affairs that inspires joyful wonder.

10:13.422 --> 10:18.130
Shalom, in other words, is the way things ought to be.

10:18.338 --> 10:19.720
I love that definition.

10:20.220 --> 10:23.484
Shalom is the way things ought to be.

10:23.504 --> 10:27.909
In the story of the Bible, the world begins as a place of Shalom.

10:28.730 --> 10:35.939
Everything is the way it's supposed to be, and Shalom is all about relationships.

10:35.959 --> 10:42.226
Relationships between God and humanity, between humans and ourselves,

10:42.530 --> 10:47.958
between genders, between classes, between races, between nations.

10:48.799 --> 10:57.832
And with the rest of God's creation, all of these relationships are rightly ordered and they're good and they're life-giving.

10:58.312 --> 11:00.856
That's the picture that we have of Shalom.

11:01.677 --> 11:07.826
But then only two chapters into the story of the Bible, this thing called sin shows up and it ruins everything.

11:08.130 --> 11:12.516
Here's how Platinja explains what sin is and how God feels about it.

11:13.377 --> 11:21.789
If Shalom is God's design for creation and redemption, sin is human vandalism of these great realities.

11:22.811 --> 11:25.955
God is for Shalom and therefore against sin.

11:26.957 --> 11:30.802
God hates sin, not just because it violates his law,

11:31.266 --> 11:39.979
but because it violates Shalom, because it breaks the peace, because it interferes with the way things are supposed to be.

11:40.020 --> 11:43.024
So helpful framing.

11:43.184 --> 11:52.258
In the biblical story, Shalom is the way things ought to be, and sin is the destruction or the vandalism of Shalom.

11:53.260 --> 11:59.730
Sin is what comes in and severs the relationships in the world as it ought to be.

11:59.810 --> 12:05.178
humanity's relationship with God, with ourselves, with each other, with the rest of creation.

12:05.239 --> 12:09.345
Sin is whatever pulls those relationships apart.

12:09.726 --> 12:13.672
And because God loves Shalom, God hates sin.

12:13.712 --> 12:18.980
Anything that disrupts the good design of His creation.

12:19.821 --> 12:27.794
And because God hates sin, He takes it very seriously, and we're told that one day He's going to rid the world of sin entirely,

12:27.874 --> 12:30.096
and Shalom will be restored.

12:31.477 --> 12:36.142
Now, the question is, is that good news or is it bad news?

12:37.643 --> 12:41.908
Do I want God to thoroughly deal with all the sin in the world?

12:43.149 --> 12:44.790
Well, that depends, right?

12:45.291 --> 12:56.882
If we're talking about the sinful, broken systems of the world that are marked by violence and greed and destruction of Shalom, then yes, I want God to rid the world.

12:57.122 --> 13:04.410
of war and terrorism and poverty and addiction and cancer and racism and human trafficking.

13:05.471 --> 13:14.601
I want God to judge Hitler and bin Laden and the KKK and Hamas and systems that empower them.

13:15.102 --> 13:20.428
I want God to deal severely with the sinful brokenness of this world.

13:22.410 --> 13:25.874
But I also know that sin isn't just something that's out there.

13:26.562 --> 13:28.924
sin is also something that's in here, right?

13:29.966 --> 13:32.909
It's not just that the world isn't the way it's supposed to be.

13:33.449 --> 13:35.511
It's that I'm not the way I'm supposed to be.

13:36.672 --> 13:44.821
And so if God is going to deal completely with sin and restore shalom, then he's going to have to deal with me too.

13:46.743 --> 13:53.650
So this is where we begin to understand that there are at least two dimensions of this thing called sin.

13:54.178 --> 13:58.222
and I'll call them individual sin and structural sin.

13:58.262 --> 14:08.953
There's other labels we could use, but individual sin means all the ways that I personally reject God's right ordering of relationships in my life.

14:10.355 --> 14:15.580
It's all the ways that I fail to love God and love my neighbor as I love myself.

14:16.701 --> 14:21.106
It's my greed, my hypocrisy, my bitterness,

14:21.378 --> 14:24.903
my lack of kindness and compassion and self-control.

14:26.606 --> 14:32.174
We're familiar, most of us, with this idea of individual sin.

14:33.917 --> 14:39.646
But then you have this thing called structural sin, the next dimension of sin, and that's the sin in the world.

14:40.006 --> 14:50.482
Sometimes Shalom is shattered not just because of one or two specific individuals, but because entire systems and structures and societies

14:51.074 --> 14:51.675
are sinful.

14:52.616 --> 15:05.152
And this is a really tough idea for lots of American Christians in particular because we tend to be so individualistic in the way that we see the world and the way that we see ourselves and in the way that we see the gospel.

15:05.192 --> 15:16.786
But all throughout the Bible, what you're going to find is that God deals not just with individual people, but God constantly is dealing with groups of people, with communities.

15:17.122 --> 15:24.831
with tribes, with nations, with churches, with families, sometimes the entire human race all at once.

15:25.893 --> 15:31.620
So think about all the times that the Old Testament prophets speak the word of God.

15:31.660 --> 15:36.666
They almost never have a message for an individual.

15:37.847 --> 15:43.634
God's words are almost always for a group, a tribe, or a nation.

15:46.082 --> 15:51.530
And it's not just the Old Testament, think about the letters from Jesus to the seven churches in Revelation.

15:52.771 --> 15:55.375
He writes to these groups, these communities.

15:56.637 --> 16:03.967
And in some of them, he confronts them for specific sins that they collectively are responsible for.

16:05.088 --> 16:15.122
And you've got to think that in some of those Old Testament nations or in some of those New Testament churches, there's at least one or two folks that are going, yeah, I don't think that's me.

16:16.514 --> 16:31.173
And it doesn't quite seem fair that God deals with communities and groups rather than individuals, but apparently God doesn't have a view of humanity that's as individualistic as we do.

16:33.016 --> 16:38.123
So we have at least two dimensions of sin, the individual and the structural.

16:38.643 --> 16:40.786
And if we plug these into our chart,

16:41.314 --> 16:55.732
Then I think, again, as a overgeneralization, we could say that mainline Christianity tends to be more worried about structural sin while evangelical Christianity tends to be more worried about individual sin.

16:56.853 --> 17:03.221
So if you asked a Christian on the left, how do we get rid of all the sin in the world?

17:04.302 --> 17:07.346
They would likely start at the top, so to speak.

17:07.874 --> 17:15.221
They would talk about these corrupt systems of greed and violence that exploit the poor and the oppressed.

17:15.241 --> 17:23.048
They'd talk about policies that harm under resource communities and corporations that are ravaging the planet.

17:23.869 --> 17:28.033
And they would say that if you could change those systems, you could change the world.

17:29.394 --> 17:37.362
But if you ask somebody on the right, how do we get rid of all the sin in the world, they would probably say that it starts with the individual.

17:38.146 --> 17:40.830
that we need to change human hearts.

17:41.651 --> 18:00.898
If everybody in the world could just meet Jesus, if everyone could know the love and acceptance of their Heavenly Father, if everyone could experience the liberation of having their sins forgiven and finding their identity in Christ, if we could just change hearts, then we could change the world.

18:03.201 --> 18:05.064
Now, which is true?

18:05.124 --> 18:06.706
Which is right?

18:07.394 --> 18:11.078
Is the problem with the systems and structures of the world?

18:11.799 --> 18:13.721
Or is the problem with individuals?

18:15.062 --> 18:16.804
And of course the answer is yes.

18:18.406 --> 18:29.158
But the Bible has a view of sin that both has to do with individuals and has to do with structures and systems.

18:30.299 --> 18:32.722
And so this is hard.

18:33.570 --> 18:39.819
especially for those of us whose faith has primarily been formed in the white evangelical church.

18:40.921 --> 18:42.163
But think about it like this.

18:42.203 --> 18:49.313
And since this is the world I've been steeped in for the last week and a half, we'll talk about the sin of racism for a moment.

18:50.375 --> 18:58.447
If you take an individual person who is racist, they have the power to inflict serious harm on another.

18:59.528 --> 19:03.314
They can use

19:04.098 --> 19:11.789
that hatred to severely harm another person emotionally or even physically.

19:12.390 --> 19:21.242
And we would all recognize that discrimination and violence done, especially based on the color of someone's skin, is sin.

19:23.405 --> 19:32.338
But what if that person, that racist person, was in charge of writing the laws for a particular society?

19:33.474 --> 19:39.542
What if that person was in charge of building companies and corporate cultures?

19:40.624 --> 19:46.551
What if they were in charge of creating policies that guided different institutions?

19:50.156 --> 20:03.474
Then you start to see that that sin of racism is no longer confined to the individual, but like a disease, it begins to spread to the institution and to the system.

20:04.290 --> 20:16.925
And even if that individual dies and the decades go by and the world changes and becomes a much less racist place over the times, those laws may not change.

20:18.327 --> 20:20.550
Or maybe some of them change, but not all of them.

20:22.472 --> 20:30.482
And so even though the people who put them in place are no longer in power, the systems and the structures prevail.

20:31.874 --> 20:39.185
systems and structures such as schools, governments, corporations, and churches.

20:41.127 --> 20:45.454
We start to understand systemic racism.

20:46.856 --> 20:53.906
In the case of our nation, our nation that we love, that we're so grateful for the chance to live in, we know that the

20:54.306 --> 21:03.358
brokenness and the sinfulness of our history isn't just isolated to a few racist people that did a few racist things, right?

21:03.919 --> 21:14.312
It's about entire systems and structures that were designed to only work if indigenous and African Americans could be considered less than humans.

21:16.315 --> 21:18.578
That they could be captured

21:19.234 --> 21:28.626
and bought and sold and trafficked and traded and used and abused and disposed of as if they were things rather than people.

21:30.729 --> 21:34.914
This stuff was baked into the core of our country.

21:35.234 --> 21:38.759
It was codified in our Constitution.

21:39.840 --> 21:47.730
This is not just the problem of a few sinful individuals that are broken sinful systems.

21:49.186 --> 21:54.478
And this is hard stuff to talk about, but if we're going to follow Jesus, then we have to talk about it.

21:55.781 --> 22:09.170
Because the sin that Jesus detests, the sin that Jesus died for, the sin that Jesus promised, he's going to one day do away with forever, infects both individuals and structures.

22:10.306 --> 22:19.158
So in Luke 18, we have a really helpful teaching from Jesus that helps us wrap our mind around this in a really, really significant way.

22:20.000 --> 22:27.310
He's telling a parable in Luke 18 to a group of people that are having a hard time seeing themselves as sinners.

22:28.411 --> 22:33.138
In verse 9, we're told to some who are confident of their own righteousness,

22:33.250 --> 22:35.152
and look down on everyone else.

22:35.752 --> 22:37.294
Jesus told this parable.

22:37.314 --> 22:42.859
Okay, so Luke can't be any clearer here about who Jesus is speaking to, right?

22:42.879 --> 22:44.561
There's nothing subtle about this.

22:45.062 --> 22:46.383
Who's Jesus talking to?

22:46.403 --> 22:52.509
A group of people who were confident in their own righteousness and look down on everyone else.

22:53.110 --> 22:54.331
So that's who he's speaking to.

22:54.371 --> 22:56.273
Here's the parable that Jesus tells him.

22:56.633 --> 22:59.876
Verse 10, two men went up to the temple to pray.

23:00.657 --> 23:01.778
One, a Pharisee.

23:02.274 --> 23:04.117
and the other, a tax collector.

23:04.858 --> 23:12.930
So two guys go into church one Sunday morning, so to speak, and we aren't told much about these two guys.

23:12.990 --> 23:17.136
In fact, the only thing we're told about them is what they do for a living.

23:18.278 --> 23:32.018
One of them is a Pharisee, a member of the Jewish ruling religious class, and the other is a tax collector, who's also Jewish, but he works for the Roman government.

23:32.962 --> 23:37.667
who at that time was ruling over the Jewish people in their own land.

23:38.869 --> 23:48.460
And so a tax collector's job was to go around and take money from his fellow Jews and bring that money to the oppressive Roman government.

23:48.480 --> 23:53.326
So to his fellow Jews, the tax collector is seen as a traitor, as a sellout.

23:53.386 --> 23:54.928
He's working for the man.

23:55.949 --> 24:00.434
Okay, so these two guys, the Pharisee and the tax collector, they go to church to pray,

24:00.514 --> 24:14.315
And by the way, this is a parable, so we're not meant to assume that it actually happened, but since Jesus is God in the flesh, he does give us a sneak peek of the kinds of prayers that God receives over the years, right?

24:14.756 --> 24:17.921
Like Jesus is like, you wouldn't believe the things some people pray.

24:18.943 --> 24:26.354
So verse 11, the Pharisees stood by himself and prayed, God, I thank you that I'm not like other people.

24:26.466 --> 24:30.372
robbers, evildoers, adulterers, or even like this tax collector.

24:30.833 --> 24:33.798
I fast twice a week and give a tenth of all I get.

24:34.319 --> 24:37.544
So maybe not a real prayer, but based on a true story.

24:37.584 --> 24:41.771
Now remember who Jesus is telling this story to.

24:42.432 --> 24:46.037
Those who are confident in their own righteousness and look down on everyone else.

24:46.658 --> 24:48.882
So he's clearly coming after these guys.

24:49.954 --> 24:56.690
But the problem with them and the problem with this Pharisee is not necessarily that the Pharisee is living a sinful life.

24:57.773 --> 25:05.170
It's probably true what he says, that he really is living a very moral by the book, religious life.

25:05.890 --> 25:09.915
The Pharisee knows that God takes sin seriously and so does he.

25:09.975 --> 25:17.666
So he doesn't steal, he doesn't do evil, he doesn't cheat on his wife, he doesn't smoke or drink or chew or go with girls who do.

25:17.686 --> 25:27.439
He even goes without food for two days a week and he tithes 10% not just of his net income, but of his gross income.

25:27.919 --> 25:33.287
This guy is living a solid, upstanding, righteous life and he is proud of it.

25:34.588 --> 25:35.890
So that's how he prays.

25:36.738 --> 25:41.002
But then in verse 13, we hear the prayer of the other guy.

25:41.022 --> 25:43.105
But the tax collector stood at a distance.

25:44.066 --> 25:51.854
He would not even look up to heaven, but beat his breast and said, God, have mercy on me, a sinner.

25:54.436 --> 25:57.239
So this guy, when he prays, he's not proud of himself.

25:58.561 --> 26:00.222
He's disgusted with himself.

26:02.184 --> 26:03.666
And what's interesting is

26:05.122 --> 26:11.708
It's not because he's like a murderer or a rapist or a child abuser or something like that.

26:12.749 --> 26:16.633
It's not because he drank too much and did something really stupid last night.

26:17.093 --> 26:23.199
He stands before God and he pleads for mercy because he knows that he's a sinner.

26:25.622 --> 26:29.886
So what is the sin that he's bringing to God in prayer?

26:30.206 --> 26:34.450
Well, Jesus literally has only told us one thing

26:34.530 --> 26:35.391
about this man.

26:37.153 --> 26:38.635
And it's what he does for a living.

26:41.538 --> 26:48.466
He takes money from an oppressed group of people and he puts it in the pockets of their oppressors.

26:51.028 --> 26:52.871
Now this guy wasn't doing anything illegal.

26:53.872 --> 26:58.777
In fact, his job was to enforce the law of the land and make sure everybody paid their taxes.

27:00.119 --> 27:03.122
And yet he has overcome with grief.

27:03.554 --> 27:09.661
at his participation in a system of justice, injustice and oppression.

27:13.185 --> 27:14.606
Here's what I think we see in this story.

27:14.666 --> 27:23.216
See the first man, the Pharisee, only sees sin through the individual lens.

27:25.198 --> 27:27.040
He says, I didn't kill anyone.

27:27.841 --> 27:28.922
I didn't cheat on my wife.

27:29.984 --> 27:32.146
So I don't have any sin to confess.

27:34.178 --> 27:40.444
But the second man understands that sin is also structural.

27:40.464 --> 28:01.263
He also didn't kill anyone and didn't cheat on his wife, but he sees how what he does from nine to five while it may provide for his family is actually an assault on Shalom.

28:01.283 --> 28:03.986
What if you were a British shipbuilder

28:04.258 --> 28:15.429
in the 1750s and the ships that you built were used to transport kidnapped Africans across the Atlantic Ocean.

28:18.672 --> 28:32.466
What if you were a seamstress in Virginia in the 1850s and the cotton you used to sew beautiful dresses was picked by enslaved Africans

28:33.410 --> 28:37.035
who were forced to work in horrible conditions without pay?

28:39.798 --> 28:44.665
Or what if you were a school teacher in Texas in the 1950s?

28:46.607 --> 28:57.001
And the only teaching job you could get was at a segregated elementary school where little black boys and girls weren't allowed?

29:00.085 --> 29:01.106
What do you do

29:01.634 --> 29:08.601
when you find yourself participating in a system of sin and injustice.

29:10.262 --> 29:14.346
Well, you can be like the Pharisee and say, hey, I didn't make the rules.

29:15.507 --> 29:16.688
I didn't do anything wrong.

29:17.429 --> 29:22.994
I'm just working hard and taking care of my family.

29:23.014 --> 29:31.442
Or you could be like the tax collector and say, God, have mercy on me, a sinner.

29:33.218 --> 29:34.640
I don't know what to do about it.

29:35.441 --> 29:46.316
I need this job, but I acknowledge that this job and this life exists within a broken and unjust system.

29:46.736 --> 29:48.939
And God, I know that grieves your heart.

29:50.982 --> 29:52.023
So have mercy on me.

29:54.387 --> 29:56.850
Here's how Jesus ends the parable in verse 14.

29:57.730 --> 30:10.985
I tell you that this man, the tax collector, rather than the other went home justified before God, for all those who exalt themselves will be humbled, and those who humble themselves will be exalted.

30:12.787 --> 30:26.802
So what we see in this story is that Jesus confronts the person who is only willing to talk about individual sin, but he affirms the person

30:27.490 --> 30:31.715
who is also willing to confess their participation in structural sin.

30:32.896 --> 30:39.184
And strangely enough, the moral of this story is be like the tax collector.

30:41.406 --> 30:47.934
Take a good, hard look at the systems, structures, and institutions that you're part of.

30:49.316 --> 30:54.141
Humble yourself and confess your sin.

30:54.161 --> 30:54.642
Why?

30:56.930 --> 31:00.717
because confessing our sin is one of the most Christian things we can do.

31:03.402 --> 31:12.658
At the very heart of the invitation of the gospel is the acknowledgement that we aren't the way we're supposed to be.

31:14.498 --> 31:29.202
And so Christians amongst all people ought to be known as those who are the first to confess our sins, the first to admit when we're wrong, the first to acknowledge our faults and failures in the past and in the present.

31:29.282 --> 31:33.108
Confessing your sin is one of the most Christian things you can do.

31:35.432 --> 31:39.218
And so this is why we practice this here together every Sunday morning.

31:40.354 --> 31:44.942
And when we pray our prayers of confession, we pray them in the plural.

31:46.524 --> 31:53.936
We pray we have sinned against you through thought, word, indeed, have mercy on us and forgive us.

31:56.420 --> 32:01.589
We don't pray simply as individuals, we pray as members of a community.

32:05.976 --> 32:07.218
Corporate confession

32:07.554 --> 32:11.819
is an exercise in remembering that sin isn't just individualistic.

32:13.220 --> 32:27.336
We acknowledge and renounce the presence and reality of all kinds of sins, which we're connected to and complicit in, which is hard to do and we'd rather not.

32:29.539 --> 32:36.146
But Jesus himself actually modeled this for us, and he taught his disciples to pray this way.

32:36.994 --> 32:49.251
Right in the middle of the Lord's prayer, the prayer that we pray every week, Jesus prays, forgive us our sins as we also forgive those who sin against us.

32:51.875 --> 33:05.394
Jesus, the one human being who's without sin, who lived a morally perfect life, identifies himself with the sins of humanity.

33:07.042 --> 33:19.257
He prays in the plural with us, seeking the Father's forgiveness for sins of which he was personally innocent.

33:19.277 --> 33:27.447
And so when Jesus taught his disciples to pray, forgive us our sins, he's teaching us that sin isn't just individual, it's also structural.

33:27.907 --> 33:36.818
He's teaching us to take responsibility for the sins in which we are complicit, even if we aren't personally.

33:36.898 --> 33:37.279
guilty.

33:39.462 --> 33:56.766
Last year, here in Antioch, we hosted an evening of learning and lament around the racist history of central Oregon, around the treatment of indigenous and black and brown people in our state's history.

33:58.829 --> 34:05.298
We acknowledged and told the truth about the reality that there's a reason bend is 91% white.

34:06.434 --> 34:09.339
That's not an accident or a coincidence.

34:11.722 --> 34:13.846
That's a premeditated uniformity.

34:15.729 --> 34:27.227
In fact, one of our civil rights hosts that we spent time with this week looked at our group coming in and said, you are the most segregated group I've ever spoken to.

34:28.809 --> 34:31.794
And we looked around and go, we're not segregated.

34:34.946 --> 34:37.269
We can't even coexist in the same state.

34:40.452 --> 34:43.916
And so we hosted an evening of learning and lamenting this history.

34:44.297 --> 34:49.863
And the purpose of doing that wasn't to solve the problem of racism, but to confess it.

34:52.326 --> 34:57.632
And to confess the brokenness in the world and that brokenness that's in us.

34:57.932 --> 34:58.172
Why?

34:58.733 --> 35:03.058
Because confessing our sin is one of the most Christian things we can do.

35:05.282 --> 35:13.453
So our hope at Antioch is to be a church that sees sin the way God sees it.

35:15.055 --> 35:18.620
A church that loves Shalom and therefore hates sin.

35:20.062 --> 35:28.834
Anything that vandalizes or violates the joyful, light-giving, righteous relationships that God desires.

35:30.477 --> 35:34.322
Which means we're gonna be a church that deals with both individual

35:34.402 --> 35:35.684
and structural sin.

35:37.086 --> 35:43.858
We're going to pay attention to the ways in which we're not the people we ought to be and the world isn't the way it ought to be.

35:45.601 --> 35:55.698
And I'll tell you, that puts us in an awkward space at times because we're committed to both personal holiness and social justice.

35:58.482 --> 36:00.786
That doesn't fit nicely in either camp.

36:03.362 --> 36:15.101
But that's where we feel convinced that God has called us to live because the gospel of Jesus is way bigger than any of us realized.

36:15.422 --> 36:17.425
And it's big enough to deal with both.

36:17.826 --> 36:21.532
And one day God is going to come and he's gonna make the world new again.

36:21.552 --> 36:24.256
A new heavens and a new earth are coming.

36:24.337 --> 36:25.939
Shalom will be restored.

36:26.420 --> 36:30.066
And one of the ways that we resist sin

36:30.178 --> 36:37.168
in the present day is by boldly proclaiming that this is not the way it's supposed to be.

36:38.991 --> 36:51.910
So confessing our sin, telling the truth, both individually and structurally, is an act of resistance and an act of hope and an act of worship.

36:54.314 --> 36:57.138
That we know we aren't the answer, we're the problem.

36:59.650 --> 37:03.454
but Jesus has come and given Himself to us and He's coming again.

37:03.474 --> 37:09.481
I want to invite you to pray with me what's been called the Jesus Prayer.

37:10.662 --> 37:22.916
A prayer that shapes the hearts, souls, and imagination of disciples of Jesus that we could become the kind of people who are the first to confess our sins.

37:23.737 --> 37:24.518
Pray this with me.

37:25.499 --> 37:28.562
Lord Jesus Christ, Son of God,

37:28.930 --> 37:31.338
Have mercy on me, the sinner.

37:32.006 --> 37:32.370
Amen.

